  footnotes: []
english:
  title: Evening View
  author: Lee Chang-su
  language: eng
  text: |-
    In solitude and stillness, a clear vista unfolds—
    In this Chang'an, ten thousand courtyards stir with spring.
    Willows drape the roads both near and far,
    And people pass to and fro in the setting sun.

    Thousands of ages have flowed through heaven and earth,
    Yet only this single body remains in the dust of the world.
    Clouds and mountains stir my spirit anew,
    And I befriend the wine cup once again.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: Chang'an (長安) refers to ancient China's great capital, here used metaphorically to represent a bustling city of the poet's time, suggesting themes of imperial grandeur and human transience.
  - key: ''
    value: 'The contrast between the vastness of cosmic time and the poet''s solitary presence reflects a common motif in East Asian poetry: individual mortality against the eternal cycle of nature.'
